<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-571-190  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 571 190.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  June 18 1990 v24 n25 p110(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Federal IS vendors: there's good and bad news. (informationsystems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Anthes, Gary H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Electronic Industries Assn releases the results of an analysisof funding patterns for the federal information systems sectorthrough 1995.andP;  The forecasting indicates that there will be growthin a few fields, but a flat market in such key areas astelecommunications and mainframe computer technology.andP;  Among theareas slated for growth are electronic data interchange, computeroperations and certain types of surveillance technologiesapplicable to the war on drugs.andP;  The figures indicate that ISexpenditures will rise from $19.4 billion in 1991 to $20.3 billionin 1995.andP;  In real growth terms however, this will equal a slowingfrom the current 3.8 percent to 0.5 percent by 1995.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information Resources ManagementFederal governmentElectronic Industries AssociationForecastingInformation SystemsBudgeting.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Low funding projections for government information systems through1995. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>